    <div class="col-md-7 col-md-offset-2" id="footnote">
      <p>
        <sup>1</sup>Modern Spanish has two genders, masculine and feminine, but its ancestor Latin had a neuter gender in addition. Broadly speaking, the neuter gender was merged into the masculine very early on, although the neuter plural nouns ending in <i>&#8209;a</i> were merged into the feminine singular, affecting words like <i>arma</i>, but also words like <i>hoja</i> "leaf" from <i>folia</i> "leaves."
      </p>
      <p>
        <sup>2</sup>The word in question, <i>dalco</i>, does not exist. In other words, it is a hypothetical word introduced to show the reader what is not true.
      </p>
